commit.message:
ci: add ARM macOS test workers

Let's stand up CI coverage for ARM macOS now that the GitHub
Actions runners are available for free.

I couldn't get the Rust backend to build trivially. Looks like it
is due to the CI workers installing a universal binary for Python
and this not playing well with the Rust build backend. Will need
more work here. For another commit.

ci: use macos-13 workers

Let's stay modern.

ci: use pip install instead of setup.py

This is the way with modern Python build tools.

ci: simplify macos build matrix

We build arm on every Python now. We can use a full matrix.

ci: upgrade actions/setup-python v4 -> v5

To avoid Node deprecation warnings.

ci: upgrade actions/upload-artifact v3 -> v4

Stay modern. Avoid warnings in CI.

Some of the wheel jobs were held back because the matrix values
aren't valid names and GitHub Actions doesn't support built-in
string manipulation functions. I don't want to think about that
right now.

ci: add dependabot

Why not.

cffi: initialize ZstdCompressionObj in an __init__

Not sure why we didn't do this before. Probably blindly copying how
the C code works.

__init__() for these isn't documented as a public API. So the
implementation details can vary.
tests: limit test file inputs to known small files

docs: remove errant entry from 0.22 section

The bug fix this alluded to was part of a separate commit. It looks like
when I cherry picked a commit I resolved merge conflicts in the release
notes incorrectly. This bug fix was definitely not in the 0.22 release.

Set correct `sys.path` prior to importing `setup_zstd`, in order to fix
building with the modern setuptools backend, i.e.:

global: bump version to 0.23.0

We just released 0.22.0. Let's bump the global version.

global: release 0.22.0

Mainly to publish Python 3.12 wheels.
ci: add musllinux wheels

global: add Python 3.12 support

Updated setup.py metadata and added 3.12 jobs to CI to ensure things
work.

Anacanda didn't work for some reason. So I didn't add 3.12 builds to it.

ci: use pip install instead of setup.py develop

This is the modern way apparently.

ci: simplify macOS wheel builds

Let's always use cibuildwheel. I think this should just work with
modern tooling.

pyproject: use pip wheel for building wheels

Apparently you aren't supposed to invoke `setup.py` directly any more.

We add a `build-system` section to `pyproject.toml` to invoke
setuptools and we replace `setup.py bdist_wheel` invocations with
`python -m pip wheel`. This should automagically use the new build-system
settings to build the wheel. This enables us to avoid complexity around
installing additional packages since the build frontend will do it for
us.

setup: look for distutils in setuptools

distutils isn't part of the stdlib in Python 3.12+. Let's try to load
setuptools's copy instead.

test: use pytest conftest.py and plugin to define hypothesis profile

This seems to be the recommended way of defining hypothesis profiles.

ci: upgrade requirements.txt

Now that we dropped Python 3.7 we can upgrade some packages to newer
versions.

global: drop support for Python 3.7

3.7 is EOL as of a few months ago. Let's not attempt to support it.

ci: add Anaconda up through Python 3.11

Let's stay modern.

ci: remove PyPy 3.7 and 3.8

These are no longer supported upstream.

ci: add PyPy 3.10

Let's stay modern.
ci: docker/setup-qemu-action@v1 -> v3
ci: actions/upload-artifact@v2 -> v3
ci: actions/checkout@v3 -> v4
ci: actions/setup-python@v3 -> v4

ci: upgrade packages to latest

This pulls in a ton of random upgrades so we stay modern. Generated with
Python 3.7 so shouldn't break 3.7.
